Here is the cleaned-up text:

To understand how the Business Owners' application works, you need to figure out how it's built. Read on to understand the Business Owners' product model.

The Business Owners line of business offers three products: Economy Business, Superior Business, and Essential Business.

The product model is like the blueprint of the application. It underpins all the business processes used in the Business Owners line of business.

Here are the top-level insured items for the Business Owners product model:

* Insured Items:
	+ NAME
	+ PRODUCT CODE
	+ PRODUCT TYPE
	+ DESCRIPTION
* Insured Item Spec: This item contains attributes from the Small Business attribute category.
* Insured Party Spec: This item contains attributes from the Business Owner attribute category.
* Insured Item Spec: This item contains attributes from the Small Business and Property Location attribute category.

The product model contains coverage specs, which define the required and optional coverages on an insurance product. The Business Owners product model contains the following coverage specs:

* Business Property
* General Liability
* Tenants Liability
* Accounts Receivable
* Rental Cars
* Employee Fraud
* Electronic Media
* Employee Auto Liability
* Valuable Papers
* Signage

The root product spec is the container for the Superior Business, Economy Business, and Essential Business product models. It contains a number of coverages, all associated with the root product.

Some product attributes are mapped to rating inputs. Attribute data is collected during a business process like quoting and passed on to product services to calculate prices.

The attribute's value data type, available values, default selected value, rating status, and other specifics are configured on the insured item spec, insured party spec, coverage spec, or root product spec.

We've set up ratings on the Simulate tab on the root product spec to simulate rating the Economy Business, Superior Business, and Essential Business product models.
title: Understanding the Business Owners Product Model
